	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>The access of foreign fleets to the Pacific is scrutinised in a new study</h1>

			
			<h4>
												20 January 2011
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>A new study by the SPC has warned that the Pacific fishing industry is poorly managed, with some stocks of tuna being dangerously overexploited: ‘the problem will spread to other species as foreign fleets clamoured for access to rich fishing grounds amid a global fall in fish stocks’. The study argues that avoiding a worst-case scenario would involve managing fish stocks more scientifically and increasing regional cooperation to ensure that the oceans are harvested in a sustainable manner. It also calls for more effective policing to curb illegal fishing, a phased reduction of foreign fishing vessels and the introduction of long-term planning in consultation with local fishing communities.</p><p>The report examines the role of offshore, foreign-based fishing, which is responsible for about a half of the value of the region’s fisheries. One of the development challenges is that: ‘fledgling local operators are unable to compete with multinational, vertically integrated companies in what are often difficult investment environments. It can be difficult to balance the benefits obtained by licensing foreign fishing vessels with the net benefits of having a domestic tuna industry, as these involve different types of benefits, incentives, and beneficiaries. There are also large challenges associated with coastal communities deriving benefits from oceanic fisheries – Pacific island countries and territories (PICTs) are unable to compete with low-wage countries in processing’.</p><p>Commenting further on the condition of offshore fishery resources in the future, the report forecasts that ‘In the purse-seine fishery, there will be continued pressure to admit additional fishing vessels in the region as foreign, locally based or domestic vessels, and older vessels will be gradually replaced by new, more efficient and generally larger vessels. These developments will result in increased and more efficient purse-seine fishing effort. Skipjack tuna are likely to be able to accommodate such increases, although the standing stock will probably be decreased, thus reducing catch rates. Impacts of the purse-seine fishery on yellowfin and bigeye tuna stocks will depend on the management of how, when and where the purse-seine fishery operates … As capacity expands, and if efforts to limit catches or fishing are effective, the scarcity of fishing opportunities will drive the incentive for both foreign and domestic fleets to fish illegally’.</p><p>The report also looks at foreign investment issues: ‘Large-scale fisheries development will be capital intensive and few PICTs will have the resources to finance the necessary investment to build domestic industries. Consequently, most development aspirations will require foreign investment if they are to get off the ground. Building confidence among investors and addressing the risk associated with fisheries investments will require the creation of an environment of effective governance and political stability.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>
The Future of Pacific Islands Fisheries, Secretariat of the Pacific Community and Pacific Island Forum Fisheries Agency, October 2010<br/>
<a href="http://www.spc.int/fame/doc/corporate_docs/Future_of_PI_fisheries_Report.pdf" target="_self">http://www.spc.int/fame/doc/corporate_docs/Future_of_PI_fisheries_Report...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>Whilst EU vessels fishing in PICT waters are relatively few, the EU is an important market for Pacific ACP fish products. One of the stated objectives of the current reform process of the EU CFP and common organisation of the fish market is that all fish products entering the EU market should be from environmentally sustainable and socially just sources. PICT ACP exporters to the EU market should give this issue serious consideration. This report highlights the challenges ahead for maximising environmental and social benefits from their fisheries, and to achieve this PICT ACP countries may need to look for international support, including from the EU. Such support should also be considered to bolster regional bodies which provide vital fisheries management and development services. Their role is crucial in analysing the comparative benefits from foreign licensing, including from the signing of FPAs with the EU, as well as in domestic fishing-industry development, and their help is needed by Pacific ACP countries in choosing the best course of action, particularly regarding appropriate investments.</p>
		</div>
		
		<div class="clear"></div>

		
